{
  "story_id": "story_001",
  "episode_id": "ep_2026-06-21-ferc-grid",
  "raw": {
    "headline_source": "FERC moves to speed grid review for AI data centers and other large power users",
    "summary": "The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission launched a fast-track proceeding on June 18 to standardize how large power users, including data centers, connect to the U.S. transmission grid.",
    "source_url": "https://www.ferc.gov/news-events/news/ferc-launches-aggressive-targeted-action-speed-large-load-integration",
    "source_name": "FERC",
    "category": "energy",
    "published_at": "2026-06-18T12:00:00Z",
    "facts": [
      "FERC ordered regional grid operators to submit tariff revisions for large load interconnections within 30 days or explain within 60 days why existing rules are sufficient.",
      "The proceeding focuses on large industrial electricity users, including data centers, that are seeking faster access to transmission and generation resources.",
      "FERC says standardized rules are intended to support grid reliability, cost transparency, and consistent treatment across regions.",
      "The order comes as AI data centers and other large loads increase pressure on power planning, transmission queues, and local utility systems."
    ]
  },
  "script": {
    "text": "Good evening. A grid decision in Washington could shape how quickly America's AI boom gets power. On June eighteenth, FERC ordered regional grid operators to draft standardized rules for connecting very large power users, including data centers, to the transmission network. Operators must file proposed tariffs within thirty days, or explain within sixty days why no change is needed. The order responds to fast-rising electricity demand from AI and other industrial loads. FERC says clearer rules are needed to protect reliability, manage costs, and give utilities, states, and customers a consistent process.",
    "headline": "FERC FAST-TRACKS GRID RULES FOR AI DATA CENTERS",
    "category": "ENERGY"
  },
